Learning Plan to fully understand Modal x Popositional Logic


Learning Plan:
  - Prerequisites:
      - Basic mathematical concepts:
          - Sets
          - Functions
          - Relations
      - Elementary logic:
          - Statements
          - Logical connectives (AND, OR, NOT)
          - Truth tables
  - Propositional Logic:
      - Syntax:
          - Atomic propositions
          - Well-formed formulas (WFFs)
      - Semantics:
          - Interpretations
          - Truth values
          - Tautologies, contradictions, and contingencies
      - Inference Rules:
          - Modus Ponens
          - Modus Tollens
          - Disjunctive Syllogism
          - Hypothetical Syllogism
          - etc.
      - Logical Equivalence:
          - Laws of propositional logic (De Morgan's Laws, etc.)
          - Proving logical equivalence
      - Normal Forms:
          - Conjunctive normal form (CNF)
          - Disjunctive normal form (DNF)
  - First-Order Logic (Predicate Logic):
      - Syntax:
          - Predicates
          - Variables
          - Quantifiers (Universal and Existential)
      - Semantics:
          - Interpretations
          - Truth values in a model
          - Validity, satisfiability, and unsatisfiability
      - Inference Rules:
          - Universal Instantiation (UI)
          - Universal Generalization (UG)
          - Existential Instantiation (EI)
          - Existential Generalization (EG)
  - Modal Logic:
      - Introduction:
          - Modalities
          - Necessity and possibility
      - Syntax:
          - Modal operators (□ and ◊)
          - Well-formed formulas
      - Semantics:
          - Possible worlds
          - Accessibility relations
          - Truth values in a model
      - Types of Modal Logic:
          - Alethic
          - Temporal
          - Epistemic
          - Deontic
      - Inference Rules:
          - Modus Ponens for modal logic
          - Necessitation Rule
          - Distribution Axiom
      - Systems of Modal Logic:
          - System K
          - System T
          - System S4
          - System S5
